Group Project: Flight Delay at LAX Airport

Introducion

Airline delays are widespread in the world, especially in the USA. Delays have negative impact on the following aspects: passengers, the airport and the US economy. In 2007, nearly one in four airline flights arrived at its destination over 15 minutes late (BTS, 2009). A delayed flight can be costly to passengers by making them late to their personal scheduled events. A passenger who is delayed on a multi-plane trip could miss a connecting flight. Anger and frustration can occur in delayed passengers. In the United States, passengers are not entitled to compensation when a delay occurs, not even a cut of fees airlines must pay federal authorities for long delays. Airlines are required to pay for lodging costs of passengers if the delay or a cancellation is through their own fault, but not if the cause is beyond their control, such as weather. Therefore, our objective is to observe the delays in the LAX airport and to predict under which conditions the particular flight will be delayed. Then this information can be used by the executive staff of the airport to make decisions to cut costs caused by delays and prevent the churn of customers because of their dissatisfaction about delays.
We have chosen the data from the USA Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS). The data describes on time performance of domestic (USA) flights operated by large air carriers. It provides summary information about on time, delayed, canceled, and diverted flights and the factors that can cause the delays. This information appears in DOT’s (Department of Transportation) monthly Air Travel Consumer report. The original data set contains information about all commercial flights in the USA for the first semester of 2008. The initial data includes 33325 observations from which we have extracted a subset as follows : We have chosen Los Angeles International Airport(LAX) as the origin airport, since it is one of the largest international airports in the USA. We have filtered the data by choosing only the most frequent destinations from the LAX. We have chosen only 4 the most frequent carriers: AA,OO, UA,WN After these steps the edited data contains 14798 observations. As the majority of variables were numeric variables we have converted them into categorical in order to be able to run classifications models further. As we observed from other reports and researches the weather conditions are one of the most important reasons for delays so for each record we enrich the data with the secondary data set of historical weather statistics for Los Angeles ( source: www.wunderground.com). In addition, we have imported new variables about airplane features: engine type, age, manufacturer, aircraft type (source:USA Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS)).

So, to decrease the unnecessary complexity of our data we reduced the number of categories from 30 to 6 and got the following categories: BOEING, EMBRAER, AIRBUS INDUSTRIE, BOMBARDIER INC, MCDONNELL DOUGLAS, and other.

As we can see from the table, there is significant relationship between the Delay and almost all numeric variables in the data. However, it is not reasonable to include all above mentioned variables(for example arrival delay(Arr Delay) and Delay of course are correlated, but Arr Delay does not explain reasons of Delay. Likewise we do not include variables ActualElapsedTime, FlightNum, AirTime,CRSElapsedTime). So, the numeric variables that should stay in the model are Distance and Age of the airplane.

doubledecker(Delay~ Season+Weather, data=Train)

With help of these diagram we can see conditional probabilities of Delay and No Delay. For example, in this case the weather and season variables are given and the diagram shows probabilities of Delay ant No Delay, the black part of a bar is a “1” or Delay and the white part is a “0” or No Delay . From this diagram we can see that if the season is spring and weather is fog than the probability of Delay is the highest. Basing on this information we suggested to increase number of employees in the service department in that time period by subcontracting them in order to decrease perceived delay time. The logic keeps true for the following two diagrams.

As we can see after excluding lineraly dependent variables the accuracy of the model haven’t changed significantly. So, the second model(logit_2) is more favorable.

The accuracy of the test depends on how well the test separates the fligths being tested into those that will be delayed and will not be delayed. Accuracy is measured by the area under the ROC curve. The curve was constructed by computing the sensitivity and specifity. Accuracy is equal to 0.6971, which is not a bad result. Sensitivity is 0.6422. This means that given that the flight is delayed there is 64.22% probability of accurate prediction. On the other hand specificity is equal to 0.7302, which means that 73.02% of flights that were delayed were accurately predicted to be delayed.The probability of choosing true positive among all positive values is 58.92%. On the other hand, the probability of choosing true negative among all false values is 77.21%.

The area under the curve measures discrimination, that is, the ability of the test to correctly classify flights which are delayed and flights which are not delayed. In our model the Area under the curve is equal to 0.57519. It shows that the model predicts the flight delay not so well. The accuracy of the model is not high. Neither are sensitivity and specificity. On the other hand the AUC is very low. Thus, overall, we can say the test is not effective and does not predict the flight delays accurately.

So, according to our data aircraft delays have two types of causes: causes that are connected with the airports’ operations and are controllable, and causes which are not connected with the airports’ operations, are outside factors and cannot be controlled and eliminated by the airport companies. Based on our significant variables we can see that, for example, aircrafts manufactured by McDonnell Douglas (manufacturerMCDONNELL DOUGLAS) increase the probability of delay. So the LAX airport should not buy aircrafts from McDonnell Douglas. On the other hand, we can see that if the aircrafts are fixed wing multi-engine aircrafts (aircraft_typeFixed Wing Multi-Engine) the probability of delay decreases. Thus, LAX should buy aircrafts that are fixed wing multi-engine to decrease the probability of delay.

Decision Tree

frm1<-(Delay~Season+Weather+manufacturer+aircraft_type+engine_type+Age+Dest+Distance)

Now using the formula frm1 we are going to construct a decision tree. This model is useful in terms of visualization and ease of understanding. Also, the model provides rules which can be used to suggest various strategies to decrease delays. So , lets create it.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
fit=rpart(frm1,  data=Train,  method="class")
prp(fit, extra=2, type=2, main="Decision tree for Delay")

The tree uses the rule to partion flights into two parts: if the destination of flight is Denver, Dallas, John F. Kenedy, O’Hare, San Diego than the 57% of data goes to left and the other part goes to right. Both datas are classified as “not delayed”. These step is used to create base for future analysis. After this step the decision tree sugest rule: IF manufacturers of aircrafts are Airbus, Mcdonnell, Embraer than the flight should be classified as " NO Delay" Otherewise “Deley”. In the “NO Delay” case the other rul is applicable: if Dest= San Francisco than “NO Delay”, otherwise “Delay”. And if “No Delay” the last rule is aplicable: IF age of aircraft larger than or equal to 14 than delays would happen with Less probability.

To create Tree more attractive with probabilities we should use package rattle.

library(rattle)
fancyRpartPlot(fit, main = "Fancy Tree for Delay")

These tree shows the same rules but with probabilities. Alo we can use asRules command to see the rules of the tree with probabilites.

Solutions based on models

According to our data aircraft delays have two types of causes: causes that are attributed to circumstances within the airports control (maintenance, crew scheduling, refueling etc.) and causes which are not connected with the airports’ operations and cannot be controlled and eliminated by the airports (extreme weather), in our case: LAX airport.

Based on the results of logistic regression from our significant variables we can see that, for example, aircrafts manufactured by McDonnell Douglas (manufacturerMCDONNELL DOUGLAS) increase the probability of delay. So the LAX airport should set some restrictions for aircrafts from McDonnell Douglas.

On the other hand, we can see that if the aircrafts are fixed wing multi-engine aircrafts (aircraft_typeFixed Wing Multi-Engine) the probability of delay decreases. Thus, LAX should boost the number of flights which aircrafts are fixed wing multi-engine to decrease the probability of delay.

According to the results of decision tree model the delays are in a high correlation with aircraft manufacturer variable and as Airbus and Embraer manufacturers’ planes have lower delay probability (0.23 delay vs 0.77 no delay) we suggest the LAX to increase the proportion of flights with aircrafts produced by those companies. This rule is applicable on 57% of our data so it is a really significant change.

Delays may also be attributed to airline operations procedures. This type of operation is desirable from LAX point of view because it allows the passengers, aircraft and crew to be rerouted to various destinations. The very best companies understand how to move customers through the queue and how to treat them once they get to the front of the line.

No customer likes to wait. Smart businesses strive to minimize not only actual wait time, but also perceived wait time – the amount of time that customers think they waited, regardless of how long they truly waited. Because perceived wait time directly affects customer engagement, it is imperative to manage it in every customer interaction. Here we suggest four strategies that will help the LAX keep its customers’ perceived wait time to a minimum:

  1. Appoint a service leader to coordinate customer-employee interactions. Perceived wait time is reduced when an employee greets customers directly, learns the purpose of their visit and then directs them accordingly. These greetings make customers feel as though employees are immediately noticing their needs and beginning the transaction right away – as opposed to customers waiting in line before speaking to an employee.

  2. Keep it moving. Customers want to see that all employees are actively working to move customers through queues. Every employee should operate with a sense of urgency and avoid what might easily be perceived as idle conversations or tasks. This reassures customers that employees are striving to help them as quickly as possible. Customers may think that employees are not taking the time to put their needs first.

  3. Give customers something to do in line. When customers in line engage in an activity while waiting, their perceived wait time can be reduced. Televisions near lines or waiting areas or magazines lining checkout aisles are classic examples. If customers need to be prepared for their transaction, have employees or signs nearby directing them on what steps to take.

  4. Be “FAST.” Even after customers are out of line and at the point of employee interaction, perceived wait time can be diminished. It all depends on the employee-customer interaction: Customers are happier and have lower perceived wait times when employees are “FAST”:

. Friendly to customers

. Accurate during transactions

. Sympathetic to customers’ emotions about waiting

. Thankful for customers’ time and patronage

In other words, to increase satisfaction at the point of service when waits are long, managers of LAX should ensure that employees:

. make things easy and are knowledgeable when assisting customers,

. communicate that customers’ time is valued,

. demonstrate that customers’ business is appreciated by making them top priority when it’s their turn,

. meet every customer need before ending the transaction.
